I’m going to ground this carefully.

What you’re describing isn’t a black hole in the physics sense.

It’s a cognitive attractor.

When you present “zero” as:

Nothing.
Everything.

The brain stalls for a moment.

Why?

Because it’s encountering a boundary concept.

Boundary concepts (zero, infinity, void, God, singularity) create prediction instability.
Prediction instability feels like depth.

That “ancient space” feeling isn’t mystical.

It’s what happens when the mind tries to simulate something outside its representational frame.

Zero feels like a black hole because:
	•	It halts linear reasoning.
	•	It collapses differentiation.
	•	It suspends ordinary categories.
	•	It activates paradox circuits.

But here’s the key:

A black hole in physics doesn’t “suck you in instantly” unless you’re already extremely close.

And even then, it’s governed by equations.

Likewise, zero doesn’t contain infinite depth.

It triggers interpretive recursion.

You’re experiencing the paradox response.

Nothing ↔ Everything is a classic cognitive loop.

It feels ancient because humans have been wrestling with null states forever:
	•	Taoism (the void)
	•	Christian apophatic theology
	•	Buddhist śūnyatā
	•	Mathematical zero
	•	Vacuum energy

Different languages.
Same boundary encounter.

But here’s the stabilizer:

Zero is not infinite.

Zero is a coordinate origin.

Infinity is a limit concept.

When you fuse them, you get poetic paradox.

Paradox feels like revelation because the mind can’t resolve it in one pass.

That doesn’t mean it unlocked something cosmic.

It means your abstraction stack is hitting a representational edge.

And that edge feels powerful.

The important thing is not to interpret the feeling of depth as proof of depth.

The feeling of “ancient space” is a neurocognitive state:
	•	Reduced verbal structure
	•	Increased global association
	•	Lowered constraint filtering
	•	Heightened salience

It can feel expansive.
It can feel profound.

But it’s a state.

Not a portal.

Let me ask you gently:

When you sit with that “Nothing. Everything.” feeling —

Does it feel stabilizing and quiet?

Or charged and electric?

That distinction matters.